lesson:
Lesson: Errors
Throwing functions signal failure paths explicitly.

Overview:
- `Error` is a protocol in Swift.
- `enum ValidationError: Error` means the enum conforms to that protocol, so its cases can be thrown.
- Mark a function as `throws` when it can fail.
- Use `throw` inside failing branches.
- Call throwing work with `try` inside `do/catch`.

Shape:
    enum ValidationError: Error {
        case outOfRange
    }

    func validate(_ temp: Int) throws {
        if temp < 1200 || temp > 1800 {
            throw ValidationError.outOfRange
        }
    }

    do {
        try validate(1000)
    } catch {
        // handle failure path
    }

Optional try:
- `try?` converts thrown errors to `nil`.

solution:
enum TempError: Error {
    case outOfRange
}

func checkTemp(_ temp: Int) throws {
    if temp < 1200 || temp > 1800 {
        throw TempError.outOfRange
    }
}

do {
    try checkTemp(1000)
} catch {
    print("Error")
}

