lesson:
Lesson: Trailing Closures
If a closure is the last argument to a function, you can write it outside the parentheses.

Overview:
- This syntax makes calls look cleaner and more like built-in control flow.
- If the closure is the ONLY argument, you can omit the parentheses entirely.

Shape:
    // Standard call
    doWork(name: "Forge", closure: {
        print("Done")
    })

    // Trailing closure
    doWork(name: "Forge") {
        print("Done")
    }

Tips:
- Most Swift standard library functions (map, filter, etc.) use trailing closures.
- It is the idiomatic way to pass blocks of behavior.

